[22:14] <Zefram> another issue: some of the documentation around errorson/errorsoff indicates that these flags are dynamically scoped (which my experimentation confirms), and says that's probably a bad idea
[22:14] <Zefram> I can tell you it's *definitely* a bad idea
[22:15] <Zefram> whether arg count errors should be ignored is generally a question of HLL semantics, hence basically lexically scoped
[22:16] <Zefram> to get the semantics it's expecting, with dynamic scoping of these flags a sub can't rely on its calling context, so it has to set the flags explicitly itself to whatever it needs
[22:17] <Zefram> but if it calls another sub, in doing so it may have screwed up the flags for that other sub
[22:18] <Zefram> the well-behaved way would seem to be to set the flags as one needs them oneself but change them back when calling other subs, to leave the dynamically-scoped state unchanged (so that the well-behaved sub is transparent)
[22:18] <Zefram> this doesn't work for two reasons
[22:19] <Zefram> firstly, the flags are write-only (absent extensions written in C), so restoration is impossible
[22:20] <Zefram> secondly, I don't think you can separate the flag state that you pass to your callee from the flag state that will affect your reception of results from that callee
[22:20] <Zefram> so it's a nasty misfeature
[22:21] <Zefram> please change it so that the flags are attached to stretches of bytecode rather than to dynamic scopes
[22:28] <Zefram> (it could have been worse, though.  the documentation for the ops doesn't mention the scoping, giving the impression that they're interpreter-global)
